The Role of Membrane Polarization in Cellular Signaling: A Focus on Action Potentials and Beyond

Abstract

Cell membrane polarization is a fundamental biophysical process underpinning cellular signaling, enabling rapid communication and functional responses across diverse cell types. This review synthesizes current understanding of membrane potential dynamics, emphasizing action potentials as a canonical example while exploring broader roles in non-excitable cells. Mechanisms involve ion channel orchestration, electrochemical gradients, and feedback loops, with implications for physiology, pathology, and therapeutic interventions. Drawing from electrophysiological, molecular, and systems-level studies, we highlight how polarization facilitates information transfer, challenging the traditional view that resting membrane potential (RMP) primarily supports excitability. 

Introduction

The plasma membrane of eukaryotic cells maintains an electrochemical gradient, manifesting as a resting membrane potential (RMP) typically ranging from -10 to -100 mV, intracellularly negative relative to the extracellular environment. This polarization arises from asymmetric ion distributions—high intracellular K⁺ and low Na⁺—sustained by active transport mechanisms like the Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase pump and selective ion channel permeabilities. Polarization is not static; transient changes (depolarization: less negative; hyperpolarization: more negative) encode signals, facilitating processes from neuronal communication to cellular proliferation. Action potentials exemplify this in excitable cells, but emerging evidence reveals polarization's versatility in non-excitable contexts, such as volume regulation and wound healing. This review elucidates these mechanisms, drawing on recent electrophysiological and molecular insights.

Mechanisms of Membrane Polarization

Membrane polarization is governed by the Nernst and Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz (GHK) equations, which predict RMP based on ion concentrations and permeabilities. At rest, high K⁺ permeability (via leak channels like K₂P) dominates, setting RMP near the K⁺ equilibrium potential (~-90 mV), modulated by minor Na⁺ and Cl⁻ contributions. The Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase actively extrudes three Na⁺ for two K⁺, consuming ATP to maintain gradients, while electrogenic effects contribute ~10 mV to RMP. 

Dynamic changes occur via ligand- or voltage-gated channels. Depolarization often initiates through Na⁺ or Ca²⁺ influx, driven by electrochemical gradients (e.g., Na⁺ driving force ~+130 mV at RMP). Hyperpolarization follows K⁺ efflux or Cl⁻ influx, restoring balance via feedback (e.g., Ca²⁺-activated K⁺ channels). These shifts encode signals by altering channel states, enzyme activities, and second messengers. 

Action Potentials: A Paradigm of Polarization-Based Signaling

Action potentials (APs) represent a stereotypical, all-or-none depolarization-repolarization sequence in excitable cells, propagating signals over distances. Initiated at a threshold (~-55 mV), APs involve rapid Na⁺ influx through voltage-gated Na⁺ channels (Nav), peaking at +30–40 mV, followed by K⁺ efflux via Kv channels for repolarization. Hyperpolarization often ensues via delayed rectifier K⁺ currents, preventing immediate re-firing (refractory period). 

Polarization here "holds" information through frequency coding (e.g., stronger stimuli elicit higher AP rates) and spatial propagation via local circuit currents. In neurons, this enables synaptic transmission; in muscle, it triggers contraction via Ca²⁺ release. Recent models incorporate mechanical elements (e.g., soliton pulses) alongside ionic fluxes, suggesting polarization integrates electrical and physical signaling. 

